reviews.review_text: 2ND STOP THIS TOUR I DID NOT KNOW AT THIS TIME THE FALL TOUR WAS GONNA BE THIS NICE.LAST NITE IN LANDOVER WAS COOL UP TILL THE DRUMS,SO WALKING IN TO THE SHOW IN CUMBERLAND COUNTY IT JUST FELT GOOD AND FROM BERTHA UNTIL U.S. BLUES IT WAS REAL GOOD.NICE SMALL CROWD,TOUCH OF GRAY WAS BORN,ALONG WITH THROWIN' STONES.THERE WAS NO SEATS ON THE FLOOR WHICH WAS HIP EXCEPT 4 BETWEEN SETS.THE BAND WAS IN GOOD SPIRITS AS WAS THE CROWD.OUR SCENE HAD NOT YET BEEN INVADED BY OUTSIDERS FOR THE MOST PART.NEXT STOP BOSTON GARDEN
Great Show Great AUD, Great Show, Add this one to your collection.
ez 5 star 5 stars for performance and vibe of venue that night... a great little experience: cap center to portland to boston

Phil Chant I was there, I have the tape....
At the end of Spanish Jam, I STARTED THE PHIL CHANT!!!!
Somebody yells, "Phiiiiiill!!!" and I start, "PHIL, PHIL, PHIL," and so does the crowd, and he comes on with MAJOR BOMBS!!!! Then they go into a SICK Other One! Huge show!!!
And when we left he venue it was snowing!!!

Touch of Grey I was at this show and remember hearing "Touch of Grey"for the first time.  I was 22 at the time and not familiar with the lyrics, I thought the Dead was signaling the end was near .   Boy was I wrong,  3/4 of the way thru the show I settled down behind the stage and watched and listened, the sound was amazing the Dead had that little fish bowl swirling , Going down the road , Moring Dew , Sugar Mag , U.S. blues I was seeing the audience just like the Band was seeing the fans . The whole place was jumping and rocking away.  An incredible sight. Needles to say " they never stopped rockin"

For Headphones Only Far from a completist, take this opinion with as much salt as needed, but to these ears this is one of the best field recordings I can recall hearing. The sense of 3D space is so (un)real. Perhaps it's best appreciated with a nice set of headphones while lying down with one's eyes closed. 

The songs that were, then, new, are still in the work-in-progress-stage, mostly, and steal a bit of momentum, but the majority of the second set more than makes up for any lull one may perceive as they perform material that they aren't a hundred percent confident with yet. The end of the show really, really puts that Dead show smile on my face. The opportunity to hear these early song arrangements is always an endearing point of the Dead.

This is not one of my more well-versed periods for the band, but this recording makes this show enjoyable as much as a concert as a soundscape. Well done. 

I kind of feel like Jerry is not able to support the song melodies as well with his voice on this date. The lyrics are there, but that old sweetness seems a bit lost from his voice. He's giving it all he's got, but a certain amount of subtlety seems to be missing. The other fantastic elements easily make up for this most of the time.

My 1st GD show (39 years ago today) Drove up from Eastern Ct College on  a beautiful end of summer day  
Ran into several friends unexpectedly.
Was familiar with their music and previously saw JGB and Bob in 1980 (New Haven Coliseum)
It was love at first sight or you can say I got on the bus and never got off
This show still rates high on my list of 125 GD shows 
A Bertha opener 
Althea
My friend Leslie was so happy they played High Time 
The Dew
Walking out the Civic Center after the show is another memory I’ll never forget 
The drive home it was an experience 
Going to sit down and give it a listen
